                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>"The gown was produced in court, and</p>
               <p>"deposed to by the prosecutor."</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I asked Mrs. Hall to let me have some money. I wanted to buy a pair of shoes. She said she had missed taking a bill, and could not help me to any money; but said, I might take any thing and pledge that I thought would not be wanted. There was a gown and a shirt of one Parkinson's, who lay down with her that afternoon; she said they would be least wanted. I took them to pledge, and the pawnbroker stopped the things. One of them sent me to the watch-house, and I was taken the next day before the justices. There this poor lady was very ill, and she was near fainting; but the justice forced her to be bound over against me.</p>
               <p>Q. To the prosecutor. Did you give her leave to pawn things for you?</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. I never did.</p>
